The little Fae folk angle has been done before and better, and the morality was rather hamfisted given Currie's stereotypical bad guy behavior. That said, I still enjoyed this quite a bit overall, largely thanks to the way the story is presented as an evolving series of events. I always enjoy this style and the opportunities for storytelling it brings, and you used it to good effect with the story here.







